Defendant Jaycey Jamie Witcher in court with attorney Danielle L. Shelton.  Jesica Ballenger appeared for the State of Wisconsin. CMC. Sentencing Proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1
The court sentenced the defendant to 12 MONTHS in the House of Correction, with credit for 5 days time served.  Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS. Probation to be served in the Mental Health Unit. Probation can be transferred to Greenlake County if accepted.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION
-Maintain employment only to the extent to still receive SSI.
-Take all prescribed medications. Any deviation from medication regiment will be considered a violation.
-Make all doctor's appointments and comply with all treatment.
-Restitution in the amount of $4,000.00 to J.J. RESTITUTION IS TO BE PAID FIRST.
-Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, restitution, and surcharges, including DNA surcharge, during period of probation. Failure to pay results in a civil judgment.
-Provide DNA Sample.

Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.

Defendant Jaycey Jamie Witcher in court with attorney Danielle L. Shelton.  Jesica Ballenger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: TC.


AS TO COUNT 1:

Parties have reached a resolution in this matter.
Plea hearing proceeded. Negotiations placed on the record and confirmed by defense counsel and defendant.

Defendant changes his plea to NO CONTEST. Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead NO CONTEST and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction. Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm, ammunition or body armor. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.

Case is adjourned for sentencing in Branch 18.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for January 9, 2018 at 01:30 pm.
